Undirected Graph (DFS)Directed Graph (DFS + rec_stack) <pre><code>def has_cycle_undirected(graph):
    visited = set()

    def dfs(node, parent):
        visited.add(node)
        for neighbour in graph[node]:
            if neighbour not in visited:
                if dfs(neighbour, node):
                    return True
            elif neighbour != parent:   # visited AND not parent → cycle
                return True
        return False

    for node in graph:
        if node not in visited:
            if dfs(node, None):
                return True
    return False
</code></pre> <p>Why check <code>neighbour != parent</code>?</p> <p>In an undirected graph, every edge goes both ways. When at node B coming from A, A will appear as a neighbour — but that's not a cycle, just the edge we came from. Only flag a cycle if we see a different already-visited node.</p> <pre><code>def has_cycle_directed(graph):
    visited = set()
    rec_stack = set()   # nodes in current DFS path

    def dfs(node):
        visited.add(node)
        rec_stack.add(node)
        for neighbour in graph[node]:
            if neighbour not in visited:
                if dfs(neighbour):
                    return True
            elif neighbour in rec_stack:  # back edge → cycle
                return True
        rec_stack.remove(node)
        return False

    for node in graph:
        if node not in visited:
            if dfs(node):
                return True
    return False
</code></pre> <pre><code>Directed cycle example:
A ──► B ──► C
      ▲     |
      └─────┘    C → B creates a back edge → cycle detected ✅
</code></pre>

